<subSubSection id="1CBB6542FFC5FF5825CAF8D4FCAFFE23" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="561" pageId="11" pageNumber="558" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="541E36C9FFC5FF5D25CAF8D4FE4EF845" blockId="11.[151,1437,1824,2031]" pageId="11" pageNumber="558">
<emphasis id="66D5EADBFFC5FF5D25CAF8D4FEB7F80C" bold="true" box="[199,314,1896,1922]" pageId="11" pageNumber="558">Diagnosis</emphasis>
(from 
<bibRefCitation id="30304B38FFC5FF5D2484F8D5FD9DF80D" author="Labay, V. S." box="[393,528,1897,1923]" pageId="11" pageNumber="558" pagination="220 - 230" refId="ref6589" refString="Labay, V. S. (2018) Cognateosymtes serraticoxae, new genus, new species, a pleustid amphipod from the Sea of Japan (Crustacea: Amphipoda: Gammaridea: Pleustidae: Eosymtinae). Zootax a, 4521 (2), 220 - 230. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4521.2.4" type="journal article" year="2018">Labay 2018</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation id="CC9A2A4CFFC5FF5D272AF8D5FD0EF80D" box="[551,643,1897,1923]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1075,1099]" captionTargetBox="[156,1431,186,1046]" captionTargetId="figure-24@2.[151,1436,181,1051]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Eosymtinae Bousfield &amp; Hendrycks, 1994, lateral view: a—Eosymtes minutus Bousfield and Hendrycks, 1994 (from Bousfield and Hendrycks 1994: fig. 7), b—Eosymtes magnumoculis sp. nov., c—Cognateosymtes serraticoxae Labay, 2018 (from Labay 2018: fig. 2a)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457370" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457370/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="558">Figs. 1c</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="CC9A2A4CFFC5FF5D279DF8D5FC80F80D" box="[656,781,1897,1923]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1798,1822]" captionTargetBox="[162,1425,201,1766]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[151,1436,181,1774]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Eosymtinae Bousfield &amp; Hendrycks, 1994: a–c—peduncle of antenna 1; d–f—maxilla 2; g–i—palp of maxilliped; j–l—coxal plates 1–3 posteroventrally; m, n, o—propodus and dactylus of pereopods 3–7; a, d, g, j, m—Eosymtes minutus Bousfield and Hendrycks, 1994 (from Bousfield and Hendrycks 1994), b, e, h, k, n—Eosymtes magnumoculis sp. nov., c, f, i, l, o—Cognateosymtes serraticoxae Labay, 2018 (from Labay 2018)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457374/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="558">2c, f, i, l, o</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="CC9A2A4CFFC5FF5D2614F8D5FCE1F80A" box="[793,876,1897,1924]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,858,882]" captionTargetBox="[155,1433,186,829]" captionTargetId="figure-24@4.[151,1437,181,834]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Eosymtinae Bousfield &amp; Hendrycks, 1994: a—urosome segments 1–3; c, f—uropod 1; d, g—uropod 2; b, e, h—uropod 3; a, b—Eosymtes minutus Bousfield and Hendrycks, 1994 (modified from Bousfield and Hendrycks 1994), c, d, e—Eosymtes magnumoculis sp. nov., f, g, h—Cognateosymtes serraticoxae Labay, 2018 (from Labay 2018)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457376" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457376/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="558">3f, g, h</figureCitation>
). Body medium, smooth. Urosome segment 2 not occluded dorsally. Rostrum short. Anterior head lobe truncated. Eyes large, subreniform. Antenna 1, anterodistal peduncular process strong.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="541E36C9FFC5FF5A25CAF869FBC9FE93" blockId="11.[151,1437,1824,2031]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="559" pageId="11" pageNumber="558">Upper lip, apical lobes slightly asymmetric. Lower lip regular, inner lobes weak, narrowly sloped. Mandible, spine-row short, with 6 pectinate blades; left lacinia 6 dentate, right lacinia blade-like. Maxilla 2, inner plate with 2 strong submarginal and subapical setae. Maxilliped, outer plate high, with one strong apical seta only and straight inner cutting edge; inner plate with 3 small apical spiniform setae and with 3 rows of 2–4 short stout plumose setae; palp segment 3 not produced distally, dactyl slender, slightly curved, not pectinated.</paragraph>
<caption id="00DE6641FFC2FF5A259AF88CFAB2F83A" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457388" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6457388" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457388/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="559" startId="12.[151,250,1840,1864]" targetBox="[155,1428,314,1807]" targetPageId="12">
<paragraph id="541E36C9FFC2FF5A259AF88CFAB2F83A" blockId="12.[151,1437,1840,1973]" pageId="12" pageNumber="559">
<emphasis id="66D5EADBFFC2FF5A259AF88CFE9EF8C6" bold="true" box="[151,275,1840,1864]" pageId="12" pageNumber="559">FIGURE 9.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="93A14D4AFFC2FF5A2417F88DFD98F8C6" authority="Labay, 2022" authorityName="Labay" authorityYear="2022" box="[282,533,1840,1864]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pleustidae" genus="Eosymtes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="559" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnumoculis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="66D5EADBFFC2FF5A2417F88DFD98F8C6" box="[282,533,1840,1864]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="559">Eosymtes magnumoculis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="66D5EADBFFC2FF5A2711F88DFDE0F8C7" bold="true" box="[540,621,1841,1865]" pageId="12" pageNumber="559">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="7DE657A0FFC2FF5A2711F88DFDE0F8C7" box="[540,621,1841,1865]" pageId="12" pageNumber="559" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, paratype, female, 4.8 mm (the shelf of eastern Sakhalin): a—gnathopod 1, b— palm of propodus and dactylus of gnathopod 1, c—gnathopod 2, d—palm of propodus and dactylus of gnathopod 1; paratype, female, 5.2 mm (the shelf of eastern Sakhalin): e—coxal plate 2 with coxal gill and brood plate; paratype, female, 6.3 mm (the shelf of western Kamchatka): f, g—inner side of coxal plate 1; scales: a, c, e—0.5 mm, b, d, f—0.1 mm; g—0.02 mm
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="00DE6641FFC3FF5B259AF95BFC65F8C9" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6457390" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6457390" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6457390/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="560" startId="13.[151,250,1767,1791]" targetBox="[151,1413,182,1729]" targetPageId="13">
<paragraph id="541E36C9FFC3FF5B259AF95BFC65F8C9" blockId="13.[151,1437,1767,1864]" pageId="13" pageNumber="560">
<emphasis id="66D5EADBFFC3FF5B259AF95BFEACF971" bold="true" box="[151,289,1767,1791]" pageId="13" pageNumber="560">FIGURE 10.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="93A14D4AFFC3FF5B2425F954FD51F88E" authority="Labay, 2018" authorityName="Labay" authorityYear="2018" box="[296,732,1768,1792]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pleustidae" genus="Cognateosymtes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="560" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serraticoxae">
<emphasis id="66D5EADBFFC3FF5B2425F954FDD9F971" box="[296,596,1768,1791]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="560">Cognateosymtes serraticoxae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="30304B38FFC3FF5B2756F954FD51F88E" author="Labay, V. S." box="[603,732,1768,1792]" pageId="13" pageNumber="560" pagination="220 - 230" refId="ref6589" refString="Labay, V. S. (2018) Cognateosymtes serraticoxae, new genus, new species, a pleustid amphipod from the Sea of Japan (Crustacea: Amphipoda: Gammaridea: Pleustidae: Eosymtinae). Zootax a, 4521 (2), 220 - 230. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4521.2.4" type="journal article" year="2018">Labay, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, coastal shallow waters off southeastern Sakhalin Island, female, 6.5 mm: a—incisor and molar of left mandible, b—incisor and raker setae of right mandible, c—maxilliped, d—maxilla 1, e—maxilla 2, f—gnathopod 1, g—gnathopod 2; scales: a, b, d, e—0.1 mm, c, f, g—0.5 mm
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="541E36C9FFC0FF5825CAFF2BFAD9FE93" blockId="14.[151,1436,151,466]" pageId="14" pageNumber="561">Coxal plates 1–4 medium, little deeper than pereon, increasing posteriorly; hind corners of coxae 1–2 each with 3–5 small cusps. Gnathopods 1 &amp; 2 similar in form, carpus longer than ¾ length of propodus, palmar margin short, oblique, smoothly continuous with densely setose, elongate posterior margin. Pereopods 3 and 4 slender. Pereopods 5–7 unequal in form; pereopod 5 the shortest; basis broadened, rounded behind, hind margin weakly serrate.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="541E36C9FFC0FF5825CAFE9BFCE6FEEB" blockId="14.[151,1436,151,466]" pageId="14" pageNumber="561">Epimeral plates 1–3, hind corners acuminate, not produced, posterior margins slightly sinuous. Uropod 3 slender, outer ramus not more than 2/3 the length of the inner ramus.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="541E36C9FFC0FF5825CAFED3FB5CFE07" blockId="14.[151,1436,151,466]" box="[199,1233,367,393]" pageId="14" pageNumber="561">Telson linguiform, apex subtruncate, with paired prominent notch; telson keeled proximally.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="541E36C9FFC0FF5825CAFE2FFCAFFE23" blockId="14.[151,1436,151,466]" box="[199,802,403,429]" pageId="14" pageNumber="561">Marsupial plates are leaf-like, broad, with short setae.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
